    "text": "When stock markets hit air pockets like the past couple of days, margin calls are never far behind. This time, banks already have reason to be nervous about lending against shares.\nInvestors borrow to boost bets on stocks, using so-called margin loans. But when prices fall investors have to either stump up more cash to repay some of the debt, or sell shares. When things move too quickly, it is the banks and brokers that made the loans who take a bath.\n...  ",
